[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1883-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1883 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 54–42 record, finishing in fourth place in the American Association.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1883-new-york-metropolitans-season] This was the first season in the Association for the Metropolitans, who had previously played as an independent team from 1880–1882.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1884 New York Metropolitans** finished with a 75–32 record, first place in the American Association.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1884-new-york-metropolitans-season] After the season, they played the National League champion Providence Grays in the 1884 World Series and lost three games to zero.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1885-new-york-metropolitans-season] The **1885 New York Metropolitans** were hard hit as manager/co-owner Jim Mutrie moved over to manage the New York Giants and took several of the team's stars with him.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1885-new-york-metropolitans-season] The Metropolitans finished with a 44–64 record, seventh place in the American Association.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1886-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1886 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 16th season of the franchise.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The **1886 Brooklyn Grays season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1886-brooklyn-grays-season] The team finished the season in third place with a record of 76–61 (their first winning season), 16 games behind the St.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1886 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 15th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 11th in the National League and the second at the first West Side Park.
[src:1886-new-york-metropolitans-season/1886-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished first in the National League with a record of 90–34, 2.5 games ahead of the second place Detroit Wolverines.
